full_text: A8: I see different representations of 24. E.g. 10 + 10 + 4 = 8 + 8 + 8 = 8 √ó 3 = 6 x 4... #elemmathchat https://t.co/OrAokL89fN

full_text: A7: Powerful way to explore multiplication concretely. Builds deeper understanding. Pics show clearly why commutative property of multiplication is true. Can see 4 x 5 = (2 x 5) + (2 x 5). In third pic, can see equivalent expressions for 8 √ó 6. #elemmathchat https://t.co/SQY7wD2Dfb

full_text: A7: 15 x 0.5 is the same as 5 x 1.5 because 5 is one third of 15 while 1.5 is triple 0.5. Keeps the balance. I know half of 15 is 7.5 and 5 plus half of 5 is 7.5 #ElemMathChat https://t.co/56cssD15jC
full_text(utf-8): b'A7: 15 x 0.5 is the same as 5 x 1.5 because 5 is one third of 15 while 1.5 is triple 0.5. Keeps the balance. I know half of 15 is 7.5 and 5 plus half of 5 is 7.5 #ElemMathChat https://t.co/56cssD15jC'

full_text: A6: 4x4 helps me to solve 8x4 because the second fact is double the first. I have double the amount of groups of 4. 4x4 is 16 and double 16 is 32. So, 8x4=32 #ElemMathChat https://t.co/g2UHwCDgiN
full_text(utf-8): b'A6: 4x4 helps me to solve 8x4 because the second fact is double the first. I have double the amount of groups of 4. 4x4 is 16 and double 16 is 32. So, 8x4=32 #ElemMathChat https://t.co/g2UHwCDgiN'

full_text: A5: The last number standing is 35. If I know that when you divide by 5 and divide by 7, the remainder is 0, then the number is a multiple of both. #ElemMathChat https://t.co/hUNSOntyhd

full_text: A3: One benefit is Cuisenaire rods are relational; i.e. Elevate a relational understandng of numbers b/c they're proportional. So, for e.g., if I decide the orange rod represents 20, what do the other colours represent? Rods also develop multiplicative thinking #MathConceptions

full_text: A1: Reflection can be integrated by supporting students to think about their thinking. How did I do today? What 'squared' with me? What's circling in my mind? What did I learn today? How does what we learned today connect to things we've learned previously? #MathConceptions
full_text(utf-8): b"A1: Reflection can be integrated by supporting students to think about their thinking. How did I do today? What 'squared' with me? What's circling in my mind? What did I learn today? How does what we learned today connect to things we've learned previously? #MathConceptions"

full_text: @mathkaveli I think it's about making reflection a habit of mind. We get better by practicing. Asking: What went well? What might I have done differently? How do I know how my students are doing? #MathConceptions

full_text: A4: 9 + 11. Could think 9 + 9  (a doubles fact) + 2 more. Hey @pearse_margie, what might another strategy be? #MathConceptions
full_text(utf-8): b'A4: 9 + 11. Could think 9 + 9  (a doubles fact) + 2 more. Hey @pearse_margie, what might another strategy be? #MathConceptions'

full_text: A3: 7 + 5 Could think 5 + 5 + 2. Or 7 and add 3 to get 10 and then add another 2. Or 7 + 7 - 2 #MathConceptions
full_text(utf-8): b'A3: 7 + 5 Could think 5 + 5 + 2. Or 7 and add 3 to get 10 and then add another 2. Or 7 + 7 - 2 #MathConceptions'

full_text: A2: 6 + 8 Might count out 6 items, then count out 8 items, and count all; Count on from 6 eight more or count on from 8; Near double. 8 gives one to 6 to become 7 + 7. 6 + 8 is the same as 7 + 7. Or 6 + 6 + 2 more; Or 8 + 8 - 2. #MathConceptions
full_text(utf-8): b'A2: 6 + 8 Might count out 6 items, then count out 8 items, and count all; Count on from 6 eight more or count on from 8; Near double. 8 gives one to 6 to become 7 + 7. 6 + 8 is the same as 7 + 7. Or 6 + 6 + 2 more; Or 8 + 8 - 2. #MathConceptions'

full_text: A1: 4 + 6 Could be a known fact. Could think near double. 4 + 6 is the same as 5 + 5. Could think 6 + 2 + 2, skip count 6, 8, 10 #MathConceptions

full_text: @themathgirl U can pick any 3 digits. Arrange the digits from greatest to least to make a number. Then arrange the same digits from least to greatest to make a 2nd number. Subtract second number made from the first. Repeat w/ the answer. Eventually u get 495. Works w/ 4-digits too. Get 6174

full_text: A8: I could think 16 - 1 is 15. Then 15 √∑ 3 is 5. Each of the 3 splats is 5 less one quarter (since there are 3 one quarters). Therefore, each splat is covering 4 and three quarters.   #elemmathchat
full_text(utf-8): b'A8: I could think 16 - 1 is 15. Then 15 \xc3\xb7 3 is 5. Each of the 3 splats is 5 less one quarter (since there are 3 one quarters). Therefore, each splat is covering 4 and three quarters.   #elemmathchat'

full_text:
A7: another way. Count up. 

1, 1 and 3 quarters, then 1 more quarter gets me to 2. Another 2 gets me to 4. So the splat has 2 and 1 quarter under it.

#ElemMathChat

3 minus three quarters is

full_text: A2: For me, the ordering requires reflection. As I've gotten older, & realized how short life can be, the list tends to favour the personal. The professional list needs to complement the personal, not compete w/ it. Not always easy. But a goal. #MathConceptions
